00:50:09,721 --> 00:50:10,920
- "Jekyll and Hyde."
- There's a scene...

1442
00:50:10,921 --> 00:50:13,620
- where good and evil fight.
- Yes.

1443
00:50:13,621 --> 00:50:16,530
So, I play both good and evil at the same time.

1444
00:50:16,531 --> 00:50:18,361
The highlight of this musical...

1445
00:50:18,561 --> 00:50:20,260
is the scene where the two personalities fight,

1446
00:50:20,261 --> 00:50:21,971
which is called The Confrontation.

1447
00:50:22,371 --> 00:50:24,740
Since this scene is the highlight, I have to perform well.

1448
00:50:24,741 --> 00:50:26,641
- Right.
- And one day...

1449
00:50:27,171 --> 00:50:30,911
(Good)

1450
00:50:30,941 --> 00:50:34,311
(Evil)

1451
00:50:34,511 --> 00:50:37,351
(He forgot the lyrics.)

1452
00:50:40,451 --> 00:50:41,451
(Shouting)

1453
00:50:41,851 --> 00:50:42,851
I shouted like this.

1454
00:50:42,852 --> 00:50:45,590
- You did that?
- All of a sudden?

1455
00:50:45,591 --> 00:50:47,961
(A roar to cover up a mistake)

1456
00:50:48,061 --> 00:50:49,931
Good and evil suddenly roar.

1457
00:50:50,391 --> 00:50:52,401
While singing?

1458
00:50:52,861 --> 00:50:55,231
There was a time when I covered up my mistake...

1459
00:50:55,271 --> 00:50:57,671
with a very sad roar like this.

1460
00:50:58,201 --> 00:50:59,940
- And...
- You did well.

1461
00:50:59,941 --> 00:51:01,270
There's a musical called "Rebecca."

1462
00:51:01,271 --> 00:51:02,640
- "Rebecca."
- You make a lot of mistakes.

1463
00:51:02,641 --> 00:51:05,740
I don't know why I only make mistakes during highlight scenes.

1464
00:51:05,741 --> 00:51:07,210
- Because you do many musicals.
- At the end,

1465
00:51:07,211 --> 00:51:09,050
something called Manderley Manor appears.

1466
00:51:09,051 --> 00:51:11,550
I show up with my wife...

1467
00:51:11,551 --> 00:51:13,320
after all the happenings have ended.

1468
00:51:13,321 --> 00:51:14,991
So I looked at the Manderley.

1469
00:51:15,991 --> 00:51:17,550
And it was burning. So...

1470
00:51:17,551 --> 00:51:18,920
It's 2am now,

1471
00:51:18,921 --> 00:51:21,891
but it is bright over there, as if the sun is rising.

1472
00:51:23,191 --> 00:51:26,160
(That's not the sun.)

1473
00:51:26,161 --> 00:51:28,431
(That's the Manderley!)

1474
00:51:28,601 --> 00:51:31,200
Then I run. Because my house is burning.

1475
00:51:31,201 --> 00:51:33,101
- It's an important moment.
- One day,

1476
00:51:33,341 --> 00:51:35,510
for some reason, I had a strange feeling that day.

1477
00:51:35,511 --> 00:51:37,871
I should say, "That's not the sun."

1478
00:51:39,111 --> 00:51:41,011
"That's not the Manderley." What?

1479
00:51:41,141 --> 00:51:42,281
What do you do?

1480
00:51:42,451 --> 00:51:43,550
I wondered to myself...

1481
00:51:43,551 --> 00:51:44,611
- what I should do.
- He said it wrong.

1482
00:51:44,751 --> 00:51:45,820
- "What do I do?"
- He should say the sun.

1483
00:51:45,821 --> 00:51:47,221
- He said it wasn't the Manderley.
- "What..."

1484
00:51:47,351 --> 00:51:48,351
What should you do?

1485
00:51:48,921 --> 00:51:50,491
"That's the Manderley!"

1486
00:51:51,891 --> 00:51:53,261
"That's the Manderley!"

1487
00:51:53,461 --> 00:51:55,631
I just shouted like that.

1488
00:51:55,831 --> 00:51:57,391
You just shouted louder.

1489
00:51:57,931 --> 00:52:00,101
- I roared.
- It makes me focus even more.

1490
00:52:00,531 --> 00:52:02,170
- I become more focused.
- He changed his tone of voice.

1491
00:52:02,171 --> 00:52:03,770
- "Rebecca."
- With a different tone of voice.

1492
00:52:03,771 --> 00:52:05,101
Sing "Rebecca" for us.

1493
00:52:05,601 --> 00:52:06,601
Rebecca Kim.

1494
00:52:07,101 --> 00:52:10,611
(The Rebecca machine is on.)

1495
00:52:11,511 --> 00:52:14,041
(My Rebecca)

1496
00:52:15,211 --> 00:52:16,711
(Standing up)

1497
00:52:16,911 --> 00:52:18,750
Come back to Manderley

1498
00:52:18,751 --> 00:52:22,221
Rebecca

1499
00:52:23,851 --> 00:52:25,290
(Thrilling)

1500
00:52:25,291 --> 00:52:28,190
I just saw this from the audience's perspective.

1501
00:52:28,191 --> 00:52:29,191
What is it like from the audience's perspective?

1502
00:52:29,192 --> 00:52:32,161
I'm supposed to see his face, but all I can see is his teeth.

1503
00:52:33,201 --> 00:52:36,271
As he sang, "Rebecca." That's how I felt.

1504
00:52:36,431 --> 00:52:37,600
- It was nice, though.
- I understand.

1505
00:52:37,601 --> 00:52:40,971
I'm not lying. I'm serious about this.

1506
00:52:41,141 --> 00:52:42,671
We've seen Yeong Cheol for a long time.

1507
00:52:43,141 --> 00:52:45,740
Even though Yeong Cheol doesn't have the ticket-selling power,

1508
00:52:45,741 --> 00:52:46,810
I don't have the ticket-selling power?

1509
00:52:46,811 --> 00:52:48,910
since there are various roles in a musical...

1510
00:52:48,911 --> 00:52:50,310
other than the lead roles,

1511
00:52:50,311 --> 00:52:53,121
I believe he could take on one of the minor roles.

1512
00:52:53,151 --> 00:52:54,720
- He is...
- Anyway, even if you are...

1513
00:52:54,721 --> 00:52:56,291
the best at musicals in the world, it can't happen.

1514
00:52:56,451 --> 00:52:58,720
You don't have the ticket-selling power.

1515
00:52:58,721 --> 00:52:59,760
- He doesn't?
- No.

1516
00:52:59,761 --> 00:53:01,460
- It's not the lead role, though.
- Ho Dong just told him to sing,

1517
00:53:01,461 --> 00:53:03,561
but when he sang "Rebecca," he really hated it.

1518
00:53:04,091 --> 00:53:05,800
Did you see that? If I didn't sing...

1519
00:53:05,801 --> 00:53:07,330
when he told me to sing, he would be really mad.

1520
00:53:07,331 --> 00:53:08,370
- But when I sing, - He really...

1521
00:53:08,371 --> 00:53:09,971
- hates it.
- he's displeased.

1522
00:53:10,331 --> 00:53:11,901
- Why he...
- So what? That's how I feel.

1523
00:53:13,071 --> 00:53:14,700
Yeong Cheol, don't you get an offer to be in a musical?

1524
00:53:14,701 --> 00:53:16,470
- You got a few offers, right?
- What?

1525
00:53:16,471 --> 00:53:18,580
I did, but I turned them down.

1526
00:53:18,581 --> 00:53:19,680
- Why?
- Why?

1527
00:53:19,681 --> 00:53:21,341
I didn't like the roles.

1528
00:53:21,481 --> 00:53:23,410
See? It was because he didn't want it.

1529
00:53:23,411 --> 00:53:25,951
- Let's just stop here.
- He's so clueless.

1530
00:53:26,021 --> 00:53:27,680
Let's listen to Sang Hun's singing.

1531
00:53:27,681 --> 00:53:28,890
- Really?
- Really?

1532
00:53:28,891 --> 00:53:30,390
Did you prepare something, Sang Hun?

1533
00:53:30,391 --> 00:53:32,720
I prepared something serious.

1534
00:53:32,721 --> 00:53:34,590
- I like something serious.
- That sounds nice.

1535
00:53:34,591 --> 00:53:37,191
- Let's do that.
- Let's go.

1536
00:53:38,431 --> 00:53:41,671
It's "The Impossible Dream" from "Man of La Mancha."

1537
00:53:41,701 --> 00:53:44,300
I'll sing for you about an impossible dream.

1538
00:53:44,301 --> 00:53:46,440
- He played Sancho.
- I played Sancho in the musical.

1539
00:53:46,441 --> 00:53:47,640
So I wanted to sing this song.

1540
00:53:47,641 --> 00:53:49,441
Okay. It's "The Impossible Dream."

1541
00:53:51,471 --> 00:53:54,980
("The Impossible Dream" from musical, "Man of La Mancha")

1542
00:53:54,981 --> 00:53:58,521
("The Impossible Dream" from musical, "Man of La Mancha")

1543
00:54:22,111 --> 00:54:28,311
(And the world will be better for this)

1544
00:54:35,521 --> 00:54:41,761
(Still strove, with his last ounce of courage)

1545
00:54:42,491 --> 00:54:48,870
(To reach)

1546
00:54:48,871 --> 00:54:52,500
(The unreachable stars!)

1547
00:54:52,501 --> 00:54:56,140
(The unreachable stars!)

1548
00:54:56,141 --> 00:54:59,910
(To reach the unreachable stars!)

1549
00:54:59,911 --> 00:55:03,681
(To reach the unreachable stars!)

1550
00:55:04,551 --> 00:55:07,881
(A beautiful performance that makes you clench your fists)

1551
00:55:07,981 --> 00:55:10,151
- Bravo!
- Thank you.

1552
00:55:10,591 --> 00:55:11,721
Come on.

1553
00:55:12,121 --> 00:55:14,761
Once he gets immersed, he can't escape the emotion.

1554
00:55:15,331 --> 00:55:17,590
He looked lost in sorrow.

1555
00:55:17,591 --> 00:55:19,700
All right. The transfer students wrote down...

1556
00:55:19,701 --> 00:55:22,200
- what they wanted to do here.
- Yes.

1557
00:55:22,201 --> 00:55:24,731
We've done "Guess Who I Am" a lot.

1558
00:55:24,941 --> 00:55:26,770
And he says he wants to do "Guess Which One is the Lie."

1559
00:55:26,771 --> 00:55:29,010
- Okay.
- Here's what's important.

1560
00:55:29,011 --> 00:55:31,981
There is a lot of too much information about us.

1561
00:55:32,281 --> 00:55:33,710
We are going to tell you three of them.

1562
00:55:33,711 --> 00:55:36,011
Two of them are true and one is false.

1563
00:55:36,581 --> 00:55:38,480
- Only one?
- You'll find the false information.

1564
00:55:38,481 --> 00:55:40,220
- All right.
- If the answer is false,

1565
00:55:40,221 --> 00:55:42,090
the information can be a lie as well, right?

1566
00:55:42,091 --> 00:55:43,450
- That's right.
- That's how it works.

1567
00:55:43,451 --> 00:55:45,461
And we have a special gift.

1568
00:55:45,791 --> 00:55:48,631
It's the tickets to the musical, "Swing Days: Codename A."

1569
00:55:49,991 --> 00:55:51,800
- Finally, Ho Dong...
- Yes!

1570
00:55:51,801 --> 00:55:53,400
Let's go see it together.

1571
00:55:53,401 --> 00:55:55,300
I'll get this right and go to the musical.

1572
00:55:55,301 --> 00:55:56,600
- Yes!
- This is what's more interesting.

1573
00:55:56,601 --> 00:55:58,700
Sang Hun and Sang Min were chatting earlier...

1574
00:55:58,701 --> 00:56:00,470
during the recess, and it was about their school.

1575
00:56:00,471 --> 00:56:01,670
It turns out they went to the same high school.

1576
00:56:01,671 --> 00:56:03,240
Yeongdeungpo Technical High School.

1577
00:56:03,241 --> 00:56:05,341
- He's my high school junior.
- We're alumni.

1578
00:56:05,611 --> 00:56:08,380
I went to Yeongdeungpo Technical High School.

1579
00:56:08,381 --> 00:56:09,711
I went to Yeongdeungpo Technical High School, too!

1580
00:56:10,611 --> 00:56:12,221
- Hey, you punk!
- Sang Min!

1581
00:56:12,251 --> 00:56:13,850
I was in the Mechanical Engineering department.

1582
00:56:13,851 --> 00:56:16,421
- I was in the Design department.
- The Design department?

1583
00:56:16,791 --> 00:56:18,460
I went there when it was next to the Yeongdeungpo-gu Office.

1584
00:56:18,461 --> 00:56:20,020
- Same here!
- You too?

1585
00:56:20,021 --> 00:56:22,131
Yes. I was in the last batch.

1586
00:56:22,191 --> 00:56:24,491
You have to give me your number.

1587
00:56:24,861 --> 00:56:25,900
(The two confirmed their bond from their high school days.)

1588
00:56:25,901 --> 00:56:27,901
I didn't know you went to the same high school.

1589
00:56:28,101 --> 00:56:29,970
- He's my high school junior.
- We're alumni.

1590
00:56:29,971 --> 00:56:32,900
I'm sorry, but did you graduate from high school?

1591
00:56:32,901 --> 00:56:34,200
You crazy fool. I graduated from high school,

1592
00:56:34,201 --> 00:56:35,511
so I took the college entrance exam.

1593
00:56:35,671 --> 00:56:37,110
(A high school graduate is upset...)

1594
00:56:37,111 --> 00:56:38,511
(to be suspected of being a middle school graduate.)

1595
00:56:38,641 --> 00:56:40,410
I'll tell you three pieces of information.

1596
00:56:40,411 --> 00:56:42,680
You're supposed to guess...

1597
00:56:42,681 --> 00:56:44,680
- which one is the lie.
- No matter how well you act,

1598
00:56:44,681 --> 00:56:46,680
- We can tell.
- your eyes say everything.

1599
00:56:46,681 --> 00:56:48,020
- Just by looking at your eyes.
- No.

1600
00:56:48,021 --> 00:56:49,490
- I'm not like that.
- He used to be Conan.

1601
00:56:49,491 --> 00:56:50,920
- Number 1.
- Number 1.

1602
00:56:50,921 --> 00:56:52,620
Unlike now,

1603
00:56:52,621 --> 00:56:56,030
I was a fashionista in my college days.

1604
00:56:56,031 --> 00:56:58,230
He didn't go to college. He keeps lying.

1605
00:56:58,231 --> 00:57:00,360
- That's right.
- He dropped out!

1606
00:57:00,361 --> 00:57:02,330
- Seriously...
- Which part of it is a lie?

1607
00:57:02,331 --> 00:57:03,800
Is it all a lie from the start?

1608
00:57:03,801 --> 00:57:07,200
- Where does the lie begin?
- I said, "In my college days."

1609
00:57:07,201 --> 00:57:08,970
- He did go to college for a while.
- During that brief time...

1610
00:57:08,971 --> 00:57:10,411
- he went to college.
- The brief time.

1611
00:57:10,511 --> 00:57:11,511
Okay. I get it.

1612
00:57:11,512 --> 00:57:14,240
Number two. I once drank five liters of water...

1613
00:57:14,241 --> 00:57:16,911
during a musical performance.

1614
00:57:17,211 --> 00:57:18,820
- That's plausible.
- That's possible.

1615
00:57:18,821 --> 00:57:19,880
- Number 3.
- Number 3.

1616
00:57:19,881 --> 00:57:23,951
I've moved 14 times in my life.

1617
00:57:24,621 --> 00:57:25,960
Which one do you think is a lie?

1618
00:57:25,961 --> 00:57:27,790
I think it's a lie that he was a fashionista.

1619
00:57:27,791 --> 00:57:29,890
I don't think he moved a lot. I bet it was about four times.

1620
00:57:29,891 --> 00:57:32,260
It's a lie even if you moved 13 times.

1621
00:57:32,261 --> 00:57:33,330
That's right.

1622
00:57:33,331 --> 00:57:34,530
- Then, number 3 is true.
- You moved 14 times?

1623
00:57:34,531 --> 00:57:36,570
Do you remember how many times you moved?

1624
00:57:36,571 --> 00:57:38,200
Numbers 2 and 3 have specific numbers.

1625
00:57:38,201 --> 00:57:39,441
- Wait. Sang Hun.
- It's strange.

1626
00:57:39,601 --> 00:57:41,301
How much does it cost to move?

1627
00:57:41,671 --> 00:57:42,870
- Moving cost?
- Yes.

1628
00:57:42,871 --> 00:57:44,911
Sometimes it costs a lot, and sometimes it doesn't.

1629
00:57:45,011 --> 00:57:46,980
How many five-ton trucks does your stuff fill?

1630
00:57:46,981 --> 00:57:48,080
Five-ton trucks?

1631
00:57:48,081 --> 00:57:49,610
It depends on the situation.

1632
00:57:49,611 --> 00:57:52,050
- Right.
- Which district did you live in?

1633
00:57:52,051 --> 00:57:53,051
When did you move last?

1634
00:57:53,052 --> 00:57:54,750
A two-ton truck...

1635
00:57:54,751 --> 00:57:57,490
- A 2.5-ton truck...
- Was it Bamgasi Village in Ilsan?

1636
00:57:57,491 --> 00:57:59,690
- I have a question.
- For how long did you live there?

1637
00:57:59,691 --> 00:58:00,960
Hold on.

1638
00:58:00,961 --> 00:58:02,130
- You know...
- You guys are supposed to guess,

1639
00:58:02,131 --> 00:58:03,190
not interrogate me.

1640
00:58:03,191 --> 00:58:04,791
- Oh, you're supposed to do it.
- While I'm on variety shows...

1641
00:58:07,031 --> 00:58:08,701
He has the face of someone who moves a lot.

1642
00:58:10,201 --> 00:58:12,441
Hold on. According to Gun Woo,

1643
00:58:12,641 --> 00:58:14,701
you have the face of someone who moves a lot.

1644
00:58:15,411 --> 00:58:16,610
- Who said that?
- Who knows what it means?

1645
00:58:16,611 --> 00:58:17,740
You have that face.

1646
00:58:17,741 --> 00:58:18,940
- Someone who moves a lot.
- It means...

1647
00:58:18,941 --> 00:58:19,941
you aren't very sociable.

1648
00:58:19,942 --> 00:58:21,680
It's my first time hearing about the face of a mover.

1649
00:58:21,681 --> 00:58:22,710
- The face of a mover.
- The face of a mover.

1650
00:58:22,711 --> 00:58:24,180
Hey, what kind of a face is that?

1651
00:58:24,181 --> 00:58:25,380
- Well, - The face of a traveler?

1652
00:58:25,381 --> 00:58:29,550
it isn't like that. There are people who look like they've struggled.

1653
00:58:29,551 --> 00:58:31,450
- He has upgraded himself, right?
- Yes.

1654
00:58:31,451 --> 00:58:33,190
- I mean...
- Is it the face of struggles?

1655
00:58:33,191 --> 00:58:35,260
Struggling and moving are...

1656
00:58:35,261 --> 00:58:36,490
- in the same group.
- That's right.

1657
00:58:36,491 --> 00:58:39,600
I think he has talked about moving.

1658
00:58:39,601 --> 00:58:40,860
- Back in the day, - That's right.

1659
00:58:40,861 --> 00:58:42,500
Sang Hun didn't have...

1660
00:58:42,501 --> 00:58:44,000
- financial stability.
- That's right.

1661
00:58:44,001 --> 00:58:45,001
- I think I read an interview.
- That's right.

1662
00:58:45,002 --> 00:58:48,540
Thus, he had to move from one place...

1663
00:58:48,541 --> 00:58:50,370
- to another.
- That's right.

1664
00:58:50,371 --> 00:58:52,210
- I heard that story.
- He must've moved a lot...

1665
00:58:52,211 --> 00:58:53,540
- when he had children.
- Yes.

1666
00:58:53,541 --> 00:58:56,250
- You drank five liters of water.
- Yes.

1667
00:58:56,251 --> 00:58:58,410
Why did you have to drink so much?

1668
00:58:58,411 --> 00:59:01,180
- You have to explain the reason.
- I couldn't stop hiccupping.

1669
00:59:01,181 --> 00:59:03,090
- You couldn't stop hiccupping.
- Is that a good enough reason?

1670
00:59:03,091 --> 00:59:04,320
You drank five liters of water for that?

1671
00:59:04,321 --> 00:59:07,320
Imagine drinking ten of these bottles.

1672
00:59:07,321 --> 00:59:08,790
- It won't be easy.
- You can't do that.

1673
00:59:08,791 --> 00:59:11,531
And he didn't drink that much water at a leisurely pace...

1674
00:59:11,731 --> 00:59:13,231
throughout the day.

1675
00:59:13,501 --> 00:59:15,130
He drank it during the performance, so it must've been a short time.

1676
00:59:15,131 --> 00:59:16,530
- Three hours.
- Right?

1677
00:59:16,531 --> 00:59:17,870
- In 3 hours.
- In 3 hours.

1678
00:59:17,871 --> 00:59:19,040
- I think I can do it.
- It's impossible.

1679
00:59:19,041 --> 00:59:20,640
You can stop hiccupping with about 100ml of water.

1680
00:59:20,641 --> 00:59:21,770
